{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477666"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:03:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:03:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14627"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14627"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.71,0.1,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57523"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7320"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42982"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1083"},{"type":"tags","id":"4318"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43545"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57523"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a seven-week history of joint pain affecting his knees, wrists, and ankles. His parent reports that he has had daily intermittent fevers up to 39.5\u00b0C, typically occurring in the late afternoon. A salmon-pink rash appears on his trunk and upper arms during these fever spikes but disappears when the fever settles. He has also experienced fatigue and poor appetite. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears tired but not acutely unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is no rash visible at present. His joints are tender but not swollen, with full range of movement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Kawasaki disease","Systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis","Acute rheumatic fever","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis (Still\u0027s disease, systemic JIA): daily fevers, salmon-pink rash, and arthralgia. The characteristic evanescent rash that appears during fever spikes and disappears as the temperature normalises is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Esystemic JIA.  \u003C/strong\u003EIt occurs on the body and axillae and spares the palms, soles and the face.  It may be mildly pruritic or non-pruritic, and demonstrates Koebner phenomenon (new skin lesion on healthy skin appearing due to trauma).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute rheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E typically follows a group A streptococcal infection and presents with migratory polyarthritis. The rash (erythema marginatum) is distinctive with central clearing and is uncommon. The absence of carditis or chorea makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E can present with arthralgia and fever, but the characteristic malar rash is fixed and photosensitive, unlike the transient rash seen here. Additional features such as oral ulcers, photosensitivity, or renal involvement would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKawasaki disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects younger children (usually under five years) and presents with fever and a polymorphous rash. Other diagnostic criteria include conjunctivitis, oral changes, cervical lymphadenopathy, and extremity changes, none of which are present here.  The fever is also not persistent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHenoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a characteristic palpable purpuric rash on the lower extremities, not a salmon-pink truncal rash. It also typically involves abdominal pain and renal manifestations, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Still\u0027s disease typically presents with a salmon-pink rash that is transient and appears during fever spikes.","The triad of fever, rash and arthralgia in a child should prompt consideration of systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis."],"references":["Kim N, Velykoredko Y, Oakley A, Mitchell G, McGivern M. Juvenile Idiopathic arthritis.  DermNet NZ.  2018.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/juvenile-idiopathic-arthritis","Chua-Aguilera CJ, M\u00f6ller B, Yawalkar N. Skin Manifestations of Rheumatoid Arthritis, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, and Spondyloarthritides. Clin Rev Allergy Immunol. 2017 Dec;53(3):371-393. \n Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28752373/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14627"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-26T18:19:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-26T18:20:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7320"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57523"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":